{"title_page": "Carl Begai", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian music journalist, and author|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{BLP sources|date=July 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name = Carl Begai\n| image = \n| imagesize = \n| caption =\n| pseudonym =\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1968|12|1|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| occupation = [[Music journalism|Music Journalist]], writer\n| nationality =  Canadian\n| period = 1993\u2013present\n| genre = \n| subject = Music, [[Heavy Metal Music]]\n| movement =\n| influences = \n| influenced =\n| signature =\n| website = {{URL|http://carlbegai.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Carl Begai''' (born December 1, 1968, in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]])<ref name=\"carlbegai\">{{cite web|url=http://carlbegai.com/welcome/ |title=About \u2013 Carl Begai: |publisher=carlbegai.com |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> is a Canadian [[music journalist]], and author.<ref name=\"myspace1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.myspace.com/usemefriendly |title=Carl Begai (Carl Begai) op Myspace |publisher=Myspace.com |date=December 8, 2011 |accessdate=2012-01-30}}</ref>\n\n== Life ==\nBegai was born in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada. He attended [[York University]] in Toronto and received a B.A. in History in 1993.<ref name=\"myspace1\"/>\n\nBegai currently lives in Germany.<ref name=\"myspace1\"/>\n\n== Career ==\nBegai began his writing career in October 1993 as a contributor to M.E.A.T Magazine, a Toronto-based metal fanzine distributed across Canada that was available for free.{{citation needed|date=July 2012}}  At the end of 1996 he joined the ranks of Toronto-based metal magazine [[Brave Words & Bloody Knuckles]] (BW&BK). He has contributed to every issue since, having become one of the key writers on staff.<ref>{{cite web|author=bravewords.com |url=http://www.bravewords.com/about |title=> About Us > Contacts |publisher=Bravewords.com |date= |accessdate=2012-01-30}}</ref> In May 2005 Begai added the BW&BK website [http://www.bravewords.com Bravewords.com] to his mag-related duties, joining other staff members in reporting metal news on a daily basis.\n\nBegai has also contributed to the regional German rock fanzine Rock City News (better known these days as RCN){{citation needed|date=July 2012}} and was a copy editor for the English language edition of the German gothic culture magazine Orkus for two years.{{citation needed|date=July 2012}}\n\nIn addition, he has written brief band biographies for [[Blood Stain Child]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dockyard1.com/bloodstainchild/bio.asp# |title=Archived copy |access-date=November 5, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070527024825/http://www.dockyard1.com/bloodstainchild/bio.asp# |archive-date=May 27, 2007 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> [[Midnattsol]], [[Scarlet Sins]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scarletsinsonline.com/2008/bio.php |title=Scarlet Sins \u2013 Biography |publisher=Scarletsinsonline.com |date= |accessdate=2012-01-30}}</ref> [[Ahab (band)|Ahab]] and vocalist [[Amanda Somerville]]. Carl also assisted Midnattsol vocalist [[Carmen Elise Espenaes]] in shaping and arranging lyrics for the band's 2005 debut, Where Twilight Dwells, and its 2008 follow-up, Nordlys.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metal-archives.com/release.php?id=66944 |title=Encyclopaedia Metallum: The Metal Archives \u2013 Midnattsol \u2013 Where Twilight Dwells |publisher=The Metal Archives |date= |accessdate=2012-01-30}}</ref>\n\nBegai is the co-writer and collaborator on ex-[[Bonfire (band)|Bonfire]] bassist [[Joerg Deisinger]]'s memoir, [[Fire And Fame]], released independently in August 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fireandfame.com/ |title=Amazon.de: Joerg Deisinger, Carl Begai: Englische B\u00fccher |publisher=Fire and Fame |date= |accessdate=2012-01-30}}</ref> He is currently working on a book of his own entitled Won't Go Quietly, a work of fiction inspired his experiences in the music industry.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.fireandfame.com fireandfame.com] \u2013 official website of the book \"Fire And Fame\"\n*[http://www.bravewords.com/ bravewords.com]\n*[http://www.myspace.com/usemefriendly myspace.com/usemefriendly] \u2013 Carl Begai's Myspace page.\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Begai, Carl}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian male journalists]]\n[[Category:Canadian male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian music critics]]\n[[Category:Canadian music journalists]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Ontario]]\n[[Category:York University alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Toronto]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian music journalist, and author|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{BLP sources|date=July 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name = Carl Begai\n| image = \n| imagesize = \n| caption =\n| pseudonym =\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1968|12|1|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| occupation = [[Music journalism|Music Journalist]], writer\n| nationality =  Canadian\n| period = 1993\u2013present\n| genre = \n| subject = Music, [[Heavy Metal Music]]\n| movement =\n| influences = \n| influenced =\n| signature =\n| website = {{URL|http://carlbegai.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Carl Begai''' (born December 1, 1968, in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]])<ref name=\"carlbegai\">{{cite web|url=http://carlbegai.com/welcome/ |title=About \u2013 Carl Begai: |publisher=carlbegai.com |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> is a Canadian [[music journalist]], and author.<ref name=\"myspace1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.myspace.com/usemefriendly |title=Carl Begai (Carl Begai) op Myspace |publisher=Myspace.com |date=December 8, 2011 |accessdate=2012-01-30}}</ref>\n\n== Life ==\nBegai was born in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada. He attended [[York University]] in Toronto and received a B.A. in History in 1993.<ref name=\"myspace1\"/>\n\nBegai currently lives in Germany.<ref name=\"myspace1\"/>\n\n== Career ==\nBegai began his writing career in October 1993 as a contributor to M.E.A.T Magazine, a Toronto-based metal fanzine distributed across Canada that was available for free.{{citation needed|date=July 2012}}  At the end of 1996 he joined the ranks of Toronto-based metal magazine [[Brave Words & Bloody Knuckles]] (BW&BK). He has contributed to every issue since, having become one of the key writers on staff.<ref>{{cite web|author=bravewords.com |url=http://www.bravewords.com/about |title=> About Us > Contacts |publisher=Bravewords.com |date= |accessdate=2012-01-30}}</ref> In May 2005 Begai added the BW&BK website [http://www.bravewords.com Bravewords.com] to his mag-related duties, joining other staff members in reporting metal news on a daily basis.\n\nBegai has also contributed to the regional German rock fanzine Rock City News (better known these days as RCN){{citation needed|date=July 2012}} and was a copy editor for the English language edition of the German gothic culture magazine Orkus for two years.{{citation needed|date=July 2012}}\n\nIn addition, he has written brief band biographies for [[Blood Stain Child]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dockyard1.com/bloodstainchild/bio.asp# |title=Archived copy |access-date=November 5, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070527024825/http://www.dockyard1.com/bloodstainchild/bio.asp# |archive-date=May 27, 2007 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> [[Midnattsol]], [[Scarlet Sins]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scarletsinsonline.com/2008/bio.php |title=Scarlet Sins \u2013 Biography |publisher=Scarletsinsonline.com |date= |accessdate=2012-01-30}}</ref> [[Ahab (band)|Ahab]] and vocalist [[Amanda Somerville]]. Carl also assisted Midnattsol vocalist [[Carmen Elise Espenaes]] in shaping and arranging lyrics for the band's 2005 debut, Where Twilight Dwells, and its 2008 follow-up, Nordlys.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metal-archives.com/release.php?id=66944 |title=Encyclopaedia Metallum: The Metal Archives \u2013 Midnattsol \u2013 Where Twilight Dwells |publisher=The Metal Archives |date= |accessdate=2012-01-30}}</ref>\n\nBegai is the co-writer and collaborator on ex-[[Bonfire (band)|Bonfire]] bassist [[Joerg Deisinger]]'s memoir, [[Fire And Fame]], released independently in August 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fireandfame.com/ |title=Amazon.de: Joerg Deisinger, Carl Begai: Englische B\u00fccher |publisher=Fire and Fame |date= |accessdate=2012-01-30}}</ref> He is currently working on a book of his own entitled Won't Go Quietly, a work of fiction inspired his experiences in the music industry.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.fireandfame.com fireandfame.com] \u2013 official website of the book \"Fire And Fame\"\n*[http://www.bravewords.com/ bravewords.com]\n*[http://www.myspace.com/usemefriendly myspace.com/usemefriendly] \u2013 Carl Begai's Myspace page.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Begai, Carl}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian male journalists]]\n[[Category:Canadian male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian music critics]]\n[[Category:Canadian music journalists]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Ontario]]\n[[Category:York University alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Toronto]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Begai"}
